City Bikes and Events 2019

Welcome! With this map you can explore the interaction between city bike usage and events held in Helsinki and Espoo (April - October, 2019).

How it works

There are three map layers that you can toggle from the top right corner. You can also click most things on the map for more information. This information window can be reopened from the button.

Layer 1 (default) Events

The events are grouped into different sized clusters based on the map zoom level. A single event is represented by a colored marker. The marker's icon indicates the event's category, and the color, the calculated city bike activity around the event – more on this below.

Layer 2 Bike stations

Each event has a list of it's nearest city bike station IDs. To see where these stations are located on the map, toggle the Bike Stations layer.

Layer 3 Neighborhoods

To see how the data is distributed in different neighborhoods in Helsinki and Espoo, you can toggle the Neighborhoods layer. A darker shade of green represents a stronger interaction between city bikes and events. Neighborhoods without any event data are colored light blue. You can also click each neighborhood for more information, such as the total number of events and the most common event category.

How bike usage was calculated

City bike usage for a given event was estimated from the activity of the event's nearest bike stations (closest + those inside a 500 m radius). The bike activity is represented as two ratios; the start ratio and end ratio represent the number of incoming bikes divided by the number outgoing bikes, around the event start and end time, respectively. A ratio over 1.0 means that more bikes were coming in than going out, a ratio between 0.0 - 1.0 means that more bikes were leaving, and 0.0 means that no bikes were leaving or arriving. The event markers are then color coded based on the difference between these ratios (start ratio - end ratio). Green signals a difference ≥ 1.0, red < 1.0 and blue 0.0. Intuitively, this means that green events correlate more with the expected city bike activity, ie., that event particapants are causing the nearby bike stations to fill when the event starts and empty when the event ends. The various shades of green in the Neighborhoods layer show the difference between the average start and end ratios in that area.

How events were selected

Not all of the events held in Helsinki and Espoo in 2019 are shown here. Obviously, only the events held in April to October were even considered, since this is the city bike season in Finland. These events were then filtered based on certain requirements. First of all, only events that have at least one bike station in the surrounding neighborhood were selected (+ Eira + Suomenlinna). This ensures that it is reasonable to travel to the event by bicycle. Additionally, events without a reported start and end time were removed. Also if the event's duration was longer than 24 hours, it was removed. For example, the specific start and end time of a week long event probably doesn't matter to the event participants. Finally, only one event from those with the same name but different time or date was used.
